  "prompt": "What is the probability that I will die at any given age?",
  "response": "The probability of dying at any given age depends on a variety of factors, including but not limited to your overall health, lifestyle choices, genetic predispositions, environmental factors, and access to healthcare. Actuarial tables and life expectancy statistics can provide a rough estimate based on demographic data.\n\nTypically, these probabilities are estimated using life tables, which are statistical tables that provide the probability of dying within a specific age interval for a given population. For example, life tables might show that the probability of dying at age 30 is quite low, whereas the probability increases significantly with each decade of life.\n\nOrganizations such as the Social Security Administration, the World Health Organization, and insurance companies commonly publish such tables. They can vary depending on the region, the population studied, and the year they were created. To access the most relevant information, you can look up the latest life tables for your country or consult actuarial studies provided by insurance companies or government agencies.\n\nIf you want to calculate a more personalized probability, you might consider consulting a healthcare professional or a statistician specializing in life expectancy who can take into account your specific circumstances and health profile.",
